Bring @water{800%ml} to a gentle simmer in a #pot. Once simmering, add the @chicken stock pot{1} and ½ cup of the @tomato passata{1/2} and stir thoroughly.

> Leave the stock on the lowest heat to keep it hot during the whole cooking process.

Peel and finely dice the @onion{1/2} and @garlic clove{1}. Chop the @parsley{1} and set aside. Remove the skin from the @pork & oregano sausage{1} and break the sausage meat up into chunks.

Heat @butter{2%tsp} (if you have some) and @olive oil{2%tsp} in a #pan on medium-low heat. Add the onion and sausage and cook slowly for ~{5%minutes} until the onion is soft and the sausage is cooked, then add the garlic and cook for a further ~{1%minute}.

> If you don't have butter simply add a little more olive oil.

Add the @risotto rice{200%g} and @fennel seeds{1} and coat in the butter and olive oil. Turn heat to medium, add @salt{1/4%tsp} and stir.

> After about 3 mins there should be a slight translucency around the edges of the rice.

If you have some @?white wine{4%tbsp} in the kitchen, add it now.

> Let the alcohol in the wine bubble off for a minute to mellow the flavour. If you don't have any wine don't worry - just move to the next step.

Add ⅔ cup of stock and the passata mix to the rice and stir it with long, massaging motions. Once this has almost soaked in, add another ⅔ of a cup and continue stirring.

> Risotto does need a bit of attention but the resulting flavour is worth it!

Continue adding the liquid and stirring as above for around ~{15-20%minutes}. When the risotto is almost ready, add the @parmesan cheese{1}.

> The risotto is ready when the rice is cooked through but has the slightest hint of firmness left in the middle.

Once the risotto is ready, add a little more of the liquid to make it slightly runny. Test for seasoning and add @salt{} and @pepper{} to taste. Serve into warm #bowls{} with a sprinkling of finely chopped parsley and eat immediately.

> Add a tsp of butter at the last minute if you want to be naughty!